====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# To confine in, or as in, a pound; to impound.
#* '''1644''', {{w|John Milton}}, ''{{w|Areopagitica}}; A speech of Mr. John Milton for the Liberty of Unlicencâ€™d Printing, to the Parlament of England''
#*: And he who were pleasantly disposed, could not well avoid to liken it to the exploit of that gallant man, who thought to '''pound''' up the crows by shutting his park gate.

===Etymology 3===
From an alteration of earlier {{term|poun|lang=en}}, {{term|pown|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|pounen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|pÅ«nian||to pound, beat, bray, bruise, crush}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*pÅ«nÅnÄ…||to break to pieces, pulverise}}. Related to {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|PÃ¼n||debris, fragments|lang=stq}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|puin||debris, fragments, rubbish|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|pun||fragments|lang=nds}}. Perhaps influenced by '''Etymology 2''' {{etyl|enm|-}} {{m|enm|*pound}}, {{term|pond|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|*pund}}, {{term|pynd|lang=ang}}, in relation to the hollow [[mortar]] for pounding with the [[pestle]].

